sec.p:
A bi-disperse model is used to demonstrate the role of interfacial tension between two types of cells, specifically the HRasV12 mutant and wild-type cells.
EVM=∑α∈WT[KαWT2(Aα−Aα0,WT)2+ΓαWT2(Pα−Pα0,WT)2]+∑α∈M[KαM2(Aα−Aα0,M)2+∑αΓαM2(Pα−Pα0,M)2]+∑<ij>Λijlij \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & E_{V M}=\sum_{\alpha \in \mathrm{WT}}\left[\frac{K_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{WT}}}{2}\left(A_{\alpha}-A_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}\right)^{2}+\frac{\Gamma_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{WT}}}{2}\left(P_{\alpha}-P_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}\right)^{2}\right]+\sum_{\alpha \in \mathrm{M}}\left[\frac{K_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{M}}}{2}\left(A_{\alpha}-A_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}\right)^{2}+\right. \\ & \left.\sum_{\alpha} \frac{\Gamma_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{M}}}{2}\left(P_{\alpha}-P_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}\right)^{2}\right]+\sum_{<i j>} \Lambda_{i j} l_{i j}\end{aligned}$$\end{document}
The first two sums are included in the standard vertex model, whereas the last term is introduced in our model to account for interfacial interactions between cells. Specifically, Λij = 0 for interfaces between same cell types, and Λij = Λ between different cell types. Using a line tension term like Λlij in the vertex model energy, where the lij is the length of an interface edge, we can obtain both segregation and spreading dynamics just from energy minimization. This term has been described as heterotypic line tension (HLT)[46]. Due to energy minimization, heterotypic interface length is minimized for Λ > 0 and maximized for Λ < 0, leading to segregation of the two cell types in the former case and complete mixing of them in the latter case.

To understand the cause and the dynamics of interaction between mutant and wild-type population in different epithelial monolayers during cancer initiation, we used a cell-based model of epithelial tissues called the vertex model. A monolayer in the vertex model has total energy given by:


EVM=∑α[Kα2(Aα−Aα0)2+Γα2(Pα−Pα0)2]
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{VM}}=\sum_{\alpha}\left[\frac{K_{\alpha}}{2}\left(A_{\alpha}-A_{\alpha}^{0}\right)^{2}+\frac{\Gamma_{\alpha}}{2}\left(P_{\alpha}-P_{\alpha}^{0}\right)^{2}\right]$$\end{document}



In the above energy function, the constant parameters Kα is the area modulus which gives the area elasticity of each cell and Γα is the perimeter modulus which give the elasticity due to the actomyosin cortex. The gradient of this energy function gives the forces on each vertex of the cell, F→(i)=−∇r→(i)EVM\begin{document}$\vec{F}^{(i)}=-\nabla_{\vec{r}^{(i)}} E_{V M}$\end{document}, where r→(i)\begin{document}$\vec{r}^{(i)}$\end{document} is the position of the ith vertex. The dynamics of each vertex position is given by the overdamped equation of motion:


dr→(i)dt=F→(i)+F→act(i)+F→motility(i)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \frac{d \vec{r}^{(i)}}{d t}=\vec{F}^{(i)}+\vec{F}_{a c t}^{(i)}+\vec{F}_{m o t i l i t y}^{(i)}$$\end{document}



where F→act(i)\begin{document}$\vec{F}_{a c t}^{(i)}$\end{document} is any active force which might drive the system out of equilibrium. F→motility(i)\begin{document}$\vec{F}_{\text {motility }}^{(i)}$\end{document} is a force which propels individual cells by F→motility(i)=v0p→α\begin{document}$\vec{F}_{\text {motility }}^{(i)}=v_{0} \vec{p}_{\alpha}$\end{document}, where p→α\begin{document}$\vec{p}_{\alpha}$\end{document} is the polarity of a given cell given by p→α=(cos⁡θα,sin⁡θα)\begin{document}$\vec{p}_{\alpha}=\left(\cos \theta_{\alpha}, \sin \theta_{\alpha}\right)$\end{document}, where this angle θα performs rotational diffusion:


∂tθα=2Drηα(t)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \partial_{t} \theta_{\alpha}=\sqrt{2 D_{r}} \eta_{\alpha}(t)$$\end{document}



where ηα (t) is a Gaussian white noise with zero mean and correlation ⟨ηα(t)ηα′(t′)⟩=δ(t−t′)δαα′\begin{document}$\left\langle\eta_{\alpha}(t) \eta_{\alpha^{\prime}}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right\rangle=\delta\left(t-t^{\prime}\right) \delta_{\alpha \alpha^{\prime}}$\end{document}.

The director of each cell corresponds to the polarization direction of the cell, which can be obtained as the larger eigenvector of its shape tensor, Gα――=1N(α)∑i∈να(r→(i)−r→0(α))⊗(r→(i)−r→0(α))\begin{document}$\underline{\underline{G_{\alpha}}}=\frac{1}{N^{(\alpha)}} \sum_{i \in \nu_{\alpha}}\left(\vec{r}^{(i)}-\vec{r}_{0}^{(\alpha)}\right) \otimes\left(\vec{r}^{(i)}-\vec{r}_{0}^{(\alpha)}\right)$\end{document}, where the sum is over N(α) vertices of the cell α, and r→0(α)\begin{document}$\vec{r}_{0}^{(\alpha)}$\end{document} is the position of the cell’s geometric center. The energy function for the vertex model used is given below:


EVM=∑α∈WT[KαWT2(Aα−Aα0,WT)2+ΓαWT2(Pα−Pα0,WT)2]+∑α∈M[KαM2(Aα−Aα0,M)2+∑αΓαM2(Pα−Pα0,M)2]+∑<ij>Λijlij
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & E_{V M}=\sum_{\alpha \in \mathrm{WT}}\left[\frac{K_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{WT}}}{2}\left(A_{\alpha}-A_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}\right)^{2}+\frac{\Gamma_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{WT}}}{2}\left(P_{\alpha}-P_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}\right)^{2}\right]+\sum_{\alpha \in \mathrm{M}}\left[\frac{K_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{M}}}{2}\left(A_{\alpha}-A_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}\right)^{2}+\right. \\ & \left.\sum_{\alpha} \frac{\Gamma_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{M}}}{2}\left(P_{\alpha}-P_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}\right)^{2}\right]+\sum_{<i j>} \Lambda_{i j} l_{i j}\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



Here, M denotes mutant cells and WT denotes wild-type cells. The index α denotes cells, and the indices i, j denote vertices and < ij > denotes an edge between vertices i and j. The parameters KαM,KαWT\begin{document}$K_{\alpha}^{M}, K_{\alpha}^{W T}$\end{document} are the area moduli, ΓαM,ΓαWT\begin{document}$\Gamma_{\alpha}^{M}, \Gamma_{\alpha}^{W T}$\end{document} are the perimeter moduli of the mutant and wild type respectively, and the Λij denotes the interfacial line tension. This interfacial line tension is only along junctions connecting two vertices and depends on the cell type on either side of the junction. Since the system we are considering is bi-disperse, the interfacial line tension can have three values, depending on the identities of cells on either side of a given edge < ij >:


Λij={ΛijM/Mif both are mutant cellsΛijWT/WTif both are wild-type cellsΛijWT/Mif one is wild-type and the other is mutant
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \Lambda_{\mathrm{ij}}=\left\{\begin{array}{c}\Lambda_{i j}^{\mathrm{M} / \mathrm{M}} \text { if both are mutant cells } \\ \Lambda_{i j}^{\mathrm{WT} / \mathrm{WT}} \text { if both are wild-type cells } \\ \Lambda_{i j}^{\mathrm{WT} / \mathrm{M}} \text { if one is wild-type and the other is mutant }\end{array}\right.$$\end{document}

In addition to this passive interfacial tension, we can also have an active contribution coming from the shape tension coupling. The shape-tension coupling is mathematically the same as the passive line tension force. The total force is given by:
(Λ+γij(t))∇→lij \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \left(\Lambda+\gamma_{i j}(t)\right) \vec{\nabla} l_{i j}$$\end{document}
γij(t) depends on the relative orientation of the cell’s director n→\begin{document}$\vec{n}$\end{document} and the edge along which the tension acts, l→ij\begin{document}$\vec{l}_{i j}$\end{document} Specifically, it has a relaxational dynamics of the form:
γıȷ˙=[γij(t)−γij0]/τ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \dot{\gamma_{\imath \jmath}}=\left[\gamma_{i j}(t)-\gamma_{i j_{0}}\right] / \tau$$\end{document}
Here γij0=−12ζ[cos⁡2θ+cos⁡2θ′]\begin{document}$\gamma_{i j_{0}}=-\frac{1}{2} \zeta\left[\cos 2 \theta+\cos 2 \theta^{\prime}\right]$\end{document} couples the tension along an edge to the shape of the cells on either side of the edge [Appendix Fig 1].

The vertex model energy can be non-dimensionalised by setting a length scale set by A0\begin{document}$\sqrt{A^{0}}$\end{document}. In our simulation we have taken


Aα0,WT=Aα0,M=A0∀α
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{A}_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}=\mathrm{A}_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}=\mathrm{A}^{0} \quad \forall \alpha$$\end{document}



and


Pα0,WT=Pα0,M=P0∀α
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathrm{P}_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{WT}}=\mathrm{P}_{\alpha}^{0, \mathrm{M}}=\mathrm{P}^{0} \forall \alpha$$\end{document}



Also,


KαWT=KαM=K∀α,ΓαWT=ΓαM=Γ∀α
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & \mathrm{K}_{\alpha}^{W \mathrm{~T}}=\mathrm{K}_{\alpha}^{\mathrm{M}}=\mathrm{K} \forall \alpha, \\ & \Gamma_{\alpha}^{W T}=\Gamma_{\alpha}^{M}=\Gamma \forall \alpha\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



and


ΛijM/M=ΛijWT/WT=0∀⟨ij⟩,ΛijM/WT=Λ∀⟨ij⟩
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \Lambda_{i j}^{M / M}=\Lambda_{i j}^{W T / W T}=0 \forall\langle i j\rangle, \Lambda_{i j}^{M / W T}=\Lambda \forall\langle i j\rangle$$\end{document}



The non-dimensionalization has been done, which defines the normalized parameters Γ¯=Γ/KA0Λ¯=Λ/K(A0)3/2\begin{document}$\bar{\Gamma}=\Gamma / K A^{0} \bar{\Lambda}=\Lambda / K\left(A^{0}\right)^{3 / 2}$\end{document}. (In further discussions, the normalized parameters will be represented by the symbols Γ and Λ.)

Although the difference in actin between mutant and wild-type have not been incorporated in the model presented in the manuscript, we could see how the actin levels change in response to the interfacial tension formed between the mutant and wild-type cells by adding a mechanochemical feedback in the model. As given in[35], we can model the behaviour of tissues using a vertex model with mechanochemical feedback. It has been shown that incorporating these feedback loops in the vertex model captures the biologically realistic features of epithelial tissues seen in experiment[35]. In particular, to model the actin distribution in monolayers with mutants and wild-type, we can use a vertex model with interfacial tension and MCFL-I[35]. When we incorporate MCFL-I in our model, we can observe how the normalized contractility Γ¯=(1/K)(1/A0)\begin{document}$\bar{\Gamma}=(1 / K)\left(1 / A_{0}\right)$\end{document}, and normalized line tension Λ¯=−(Γ/K)(P0/A03/2)\begin{document}$\bar{\Lambda}=-(\Gamma / K)\left(P_{0} / A_{0}^{3 / 2}\right)$\end{document} changes with different line tensions. The normalized contractility is associated with the bulk actin or the bulk compressibility, and the normalized line tension is associated with the junctional actin of the cells. The equations for MCFL-I can be written as:
τAA0˙=−[A0−A^0]τPP0˙=−[P0−P^0] \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} \tau_{A} \dot{A_{0}} & =-\left[A_{0}-\hat{A}_{0}\right] \\ \tau_{P} \dot{P_{0}} & =-\left[P_{0}-\hat{P}_{0}\right]\end{aligned}$$\end{document}
Thus, with MCFLs, the vertex model does not have fixed A0 and P0. The cells dynamically change these parameters depending on the vertex model dynamics. The constitutive relations for the Â0 and P^0\begin{document}$\widehat{P}_{0}$\end{document} are given below[35]:
A^0=2a0pboundP^0=2q0a0(1−pbound) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{gathered}\hat{A}_{0}=2 a_{0} p_{\text {bound }} \\ \hat{P}_{0}=2 q_{0} \sqrt{a_{0}}\left(1-p_{\text {bound }}\right)\end{gathered}$$\end{document}
Here, pbound = 1/ (1 + (A/Â)2), which is the probability of myosin binding and Â is a model parameter which depends on the dissociation constant of myosin[35]. We consider Â to the be the same for both mutant and wild-type (Â = 1.3). A positive differential interfacial tension can lead to compression (decrease in area) of the mutants whereas a negative differential interfacial tension can lead to relaxation of cell area of the mutants. This will lead to different A0 and P0 across the monolayer, and thus different Γ¯\begin{document}$\bar{\Gamma}$\end{document} and Λ¯\begin{document}$\bar{\Lambda}$\end{document}, which provides an understanding of the different actin levels.
